  "Question": "<p>Let a family have two children. It is known that one of the children is a boy. What is the probability that both the children are boys.</p> <p>So for this we build the sample space <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_595\"><math alttext=\"S=\\{(b,b)(b,g)(g,g)\\}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mrow><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>g</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>g</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>Let our event E be the case where both children are boys</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_596\"><math alttext=\"E=\\{(b,b)\\}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>Let the conditional be F</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_597\"><math alttext=\"F=\\{(b,g),(b,b)\\}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>g</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>Hence <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_598\"><math alttext=\"P(E|F)=\\frac{P(E\\cap F)}{P(F)}=\\frac{1/3}{2/3}=\\frac{1}{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo lspace=\"2.5pt\" rspace=\"2.5pt\" stretchy=\"false\">|</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>\u2229</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>But the answer in my book is given as <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_599\"><math alttext=\"\\frac{1}{3}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></semantics></math></span> and I can't seem to understand why.</p>",
